      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemical Insight\n\nThis large difference is expected from the denticity of the two ligands. **EDTA is hexadentate** (4 carboxylate + 2 amine donors), while **NTA is tetradentate** (3 carboxylate + 1 amine donor). The two additional donor atoms in EDTA provide extra chelate rings around Fe³⁺, massively boosting thermodynamic stability via the **chelate effect**. This is why EDTA is the preferred chelator in analytical chemistry (e.g., complexometric titrations of Fe³⁺), water treatment, and clinical iron-overload therapies, whereas NTA, though a respectable chelator, simply cannot match EDTA's grip on this hard, highly charged metal ion.",
